# macOS 14 compatibility and test builds

Jot targets macOS 14+ (deployment target in project.pbxproj lines 350, 409) but primary development is on macOS 26. The user has a second Mac running macOS 14 (Apple Silicon) for compatibility testing.

**Why:** The app uses Liquid Glass (macOS 26+), FoundationModels (macOS 26+), and other new APIs. All must be behind `#available` or `#if canImport` guards. Regular testing on macOS 14 catches unguarded API usage.

**How to apply:**

## Build for macOS 14

Use `-target Jot` (not `-scheme Jot`) to skip the ShareExtension which has deployment target 26.2:
```bash
xcodebuild -project Jot.xcodeproj -target Jot -configuration Debug build
```

## Package and ship

Ad-hoc sign (deep) and use `ditto` (not `zip` -- `ditto` preserves resource forks):
```bash
cd build/Debug
codesign --force --deep --sign - Jot.app
ditto -c -k --sequesterRsrc --keepParent Jot.app ~/Desktop/Jot-macOS14-Debug.zip
```

On the macOS 14 machine after unzipping:
```bash
xattr -cr Jot.app
```
Then right-click > Open (bypasses Gatekeeper for dev-signed apps).

## FoundationModels guard (added 2026-03-26)

`AppleIntelligenceService.swift` wraps `import FoundationModels`, all `@Generable`/`@Guide` structs, and `LanguageModelSession` methods in `#if canImport(FoundationModels)`. The `#else` stubs throw `.unavailable(...)`. The framework is weak-linked (`LC_LOAD_WEAK_DYLIB`) so the binary loads fine on macOS 14.

## Known gotchas

- ShareExtension has `MACOSX_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET = 26.2` -- never build it for macOS 14
- `SWIFT_DEFAULT_ACTOR_ISOLATION = MainActor` is a compile-time setting, not a runtime requirement -- fine with Xcode 26 targeting macOS 14
- The `zip` command breaks code signatures (strips resource forks); always use `ditto`
